    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Teenagers and Prayer</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>John L Powell letter comments on August 29 editorial opposing prayers at high school football games</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Prayers at Football Games'' (editorial, Aug. 29):</p>
        <p>Teenagers are known for their susceptibility to the seductions of ''sacrificing a life of virtue for a few moments of pleasure'' (as it used to be said), but the willingness to sacrifice what is best in Christianity, going back 2,000 years to Jesus himself -- concern for the outsider and especially the religious outcast -- for the pleasures of group prayer before a football game is beyond belief.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Prayers at Football Games'' (editorial, Aug. 29):</p>
        <p>Teenagers are known for their susceptibility to the seductions of ''sacrificing a life of virtue for a few moments of pleasure'' (as it used to be said), but the willingness to sacrifice what is best in Christianity, going back 2,000 years to Jesus himself -- concern for the outsider and especially the religious outcast -- for the pleasures of group prayer before a football game is beyond belief.</p>
        <p>Adults who exploit youthful enthusiasm, idealism and strength to serve their own ends, passing off group prayer before a football game as religious ecstasy, steal what is most precious from teenagers and deprive society of the energy and vision for renewal it will find nowhere else. Have these adults no conscience?</p>
        <p>JOHN L. POWELL  Princeton, N.J., Aug. 29, 2000</p>
      </block>
